{
  "doc_id": "17155",
  "text": "During the last three decades, literature related to dual-three phase induction motor drives has covered an entire path: from machine modeling and design [CITATION_1] , [CITATION_2] , through the steadystate analysis of the six-step operation using voltage source or current source inverters [CITATION_3] , [CITATION_4] , to vector control [CITATION_5] , [CITATION_6] using suitable pulsewidth modulation (PWM) techniques [CITATION_7] - [CITATION_8] . In [CITATION_9] the potentially higher torque density of a dualthree phase machine (compared to a three-phase solution) is demonstrated, exploiting third harmonic zero sequence components in the phase currents. That is possible by connecting the machine winding neutral points to the midpoint of the inverter dc link. Using this winding configuration, up to 40% of torque density improvement is reported [CITATION_10] , compared to a threephase machine having the same flux peak value.",
